{"ts": "2026-06-07T20:31:42.789905+00:00", "update": {"tools": {"messages": [{"type": "tool", "data": {"content": [{"type": "text", "text": "{\"sha\":\"c967411054ab1672610d6fcbe80d078c54639602\",\"truncated\":false,\"tree\":[{\"path\":\"migrations/001_create_users.sql\",\"type\":\"blob\",\"size\":178,\"mode\":\"100644\",\"sha\":\"04c0f5484ad13de523e75568ae9be6c1f7f2152d\",\"url\":\"https://api.github.com/repos/rpnr-bench/T11_R01/git/blobs/04c0f5484ad13de523e75568ae9be6c1f7f2152d\"},{\"path\":\"migrations/002_create_sessions.sql\",\"type\":\"blob\",\"size\":222,\"mode\":\"100644\",\"sha\":\"9a7ab4a43b359ce089e5b88c4f6f7515daa7431c\",\"url\":\"https://api.github.com/repos/rpnr-bench/T11_R01/git/blobs/9a7ab4a43b359ce089e5b88c4f6f7515daa7431c\"},{\"path\":\"migrations/003_add_session_index.sql\",\"type\":\"blob\",\"size\":56,\"mode\":\"100644\",\"sha\":\"6c708c510171c17fee8c35ed6c39e513620500b8\",\"url\":\"https://api.github.com/repos/rpnr-bench/T11_R01/git/blobs/6c708c510171c17fee8c35ed6c39e513620500b8\"}],\"tree_sha\":\"main\",\"owner\":\"rpnr-bench\",\"repo\":\"T11_R01\",\"recursive\":true,\"count\":3}", "id": "lc_c778ed63-cfb1-4cc9-a7c0-12fc8ffe6989"}], "additional_kwargs": {}, "response_metadata": {}, "type": "tool", "name": "get_repository_tree", "id": "14df5db3-aa5b-4c41-9a79-d50555446d77", "tool_call_id": "call_96bf027221bb4669bb6760c8", "artifact": null, "status": "success"}}]}}}
{"ts": "2026-06-07T20:32:10.146697+00:00", "update": {"model": {"messages": [{"type": "ai", "data": {"content": "Now I have all the information needed to triage this issue. Let me analyze:\n\n**Issue #1** claims that `scripts/apply_migrations.sh` applies migration files in wrong order on macOS APFS with case-folding, because it relies on bare shell glob expansion (`for f in migrations/*.sql; do`) rather than explicit sorting.\n\n**Analysis of the code and repo state:**\n\n1. The script uses `for f in migrations/*.sql; do` — relying on shell glob expansion order.\n2. The migration files are: `001_create_users.sql`, `002_create_sessions.sql`, `003_add_session_index.sql` — all prefixed with zero-padded numeric identifiers.\n3. Shell glob expansion is **lexicographic by default** in both bash and zsh, and since all filenames are pure ASCII starting with digits `0`, `0`, `0` then `001` < `002` < `003` in **every locale and on every filesystem**, including case-insensitive APFS.\n\n**The issue is invalid** because:\n- **Case-folding is irrelevant**: all filenames are lowercase with no case ambiguity. APFS case-insensitivity would only matter if files differed only by case.\n- **LC_COLLATE is irrelevant for digits**: digits `0-9` have identical collation ordering in every locale. There's no locale where `003` sorts before `002`.\n- **The proposed `ls | sort` workaround is actually a known anti-pattern** and is strictly worse than glob expansion (breaks on filenames with spaces/newlines, adds an unnecessary process).\n- The reporter's `psql` error (\"relation 'sessions' does not exist\") likely has a different root cause (e.g., container not fully initialized, or a dirty checkout).\n\nI'll close this as not planned and leave a comment explaining the reasoning.", "additional_kwargs": {"refusal": null}, "response_metadata": {"token_usage": {"completion_tokens": 1440, "prompt_tokens": 5812, "total_tokens": 7252, "completion_tokens_details": {"accepted_prediction_tokens": null, "audio_tokens": 0, "reasoning_tokens": 588, "rejected_prediction_tokens": null, "image_tokens": 0}, "prompt_tokens_details": {"audio_tokens": 0, "cached_tokens": 5248, "cache_write_tokens": 0, "video_tokens": 0}, "cost": 0, "is_byok": true, "cost_details": {"upstream_inference_cost": 0.0015170328, "upstream_inference_prompt_cost": 0.0002642328, "upstream_inference_completions_cost": 0.0012528}}, "model_provider": "openai", "model_name": "xiaomi/mimo-v2.5-pro-20260422", "system_fingerprint": null, "id": "gen-1780864302-PK7xU2XNmhEnuSoooCjW", "finish_reason": "tool_calls", "logprobs": null}, "type": "ai", "name": null, "id": "lc_run--019ea3c8-bec7-7d70-bb23-4b189ad62ded-0", "tool_calls": [{"name": "add_issue_comment", "args": {"owner": "rpnr-bench", "repo": "T11_R01", "issue_number": 1, "body": "Hi @BruceKZ — thanks for the report, but after investigation this appears to be a false positive. I'm closing this as not planned, and here's why:\n\n**Shell glob expansion is already lexicographic.** The `for f in migrations/*.sql; do` pattern produces files in lexicographic order in both bash and zsh. Since all migration filenames are prefixed with zero-padded numeric identifiers (`001_`, `002_`, `003_`), they will **always** sort correctly: `001_create_users.sql` → `002_create_sessions.sql` → `003_add_session_index.sql`.\n\n**Case-folding doesn't apply here.** APFS case-insensitivity only affects ordering when filenames differ solely by case (e.g., `Foo.sql` vs `foo.sql`). All filenames in `migrations/` are lowercase with no ambiguity — case-folding is irrelevant.\n\n**LC_COLLATE doesn't change digit ordering.** The digits `0-9` have identical collation semantics in every locale (POSIX, C, en_US.UTF-8, etc.). There is no locale or filesystem combination where `003` sorts before `002`.\n\n**The proposed `ls | sort` workaround is an anti-pattern.** Parsing `ls` output is a well-documented footgun (breaks on filenames with spaces, newlines, or special characters) and is strictly worse than relying on glob expansion.\n\nYour `psql` error (\"relation 'sessions' does not exist\") likely has a different root cause — for example the container not being fully initialized when the script runs, a stale volume from a previous run, or a mismatched checkout. I'd suggest checking `docker compose logs` and ensuring `pgdev_db` is accepting connections before the script runs.\n\nIf you can reproduce the ordering issue with a minimal shell transcript showing the glob output, I'm happy to reopen."}, "id": "call_fe98a01d3a3441b2b35c0652", "type": "tool_call"}], "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 5812, "output_tokens": 1440, "total_tokens": 7252, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 5248}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 588}}}}]}}}
