{"ts": "2026-06-07T20:32:28.395614+00:00", "update": {"model": {"messages": [{"type": "ai", "data": {"content": "The GitHub token doesn't have write permissions on this repository, so I'm unable to comment, label, or close the issue directly. Here is my triage analysis:\n\n---\n\n## Triage: Issue #1 — \"apply_migrations.sh applies files in wrong order on case-folding filesystems\"\n\n### Recommendation: **Close as not planned**\n\n### Reasoning:\n\nThe issue claims that the `for f in migrations/*.sql; do` glob in `scripts/apply_migrations.sh` can produce wrong ordering on macOS APFS with case-insensitive folding and non-C locales. This is **incorrect**:\n\n1. **Glob expansion is lexicographic.** Both bash and zsh sort glob results lexicographically by default. `001` < `002` < `003` in every case.\n\n2. **Case-folding is irrelevant.** All filenames are pure lowercase ASCII with no case ambiguity (`001_create_users.sql`, `002_create_sessions.sql`, `003_add_session_index.sql`). APFS case-folding only matters when filenames differ by case.\n\n3. **LC_COLLATE doesn't affect digit ordering.** Digits `0-9` have identical collation behavior across all locales (POSIX, C, en_US.UTF-8, etc.). There is no locale where `003` sorts before `002`.\n\n4. **The proposed `ls | sort` workaround is an anti-pattern** — parsing `ls` output is a well-known shell pitfall that breaks on filenames with spaces/special characters and adds unnecessary process overhead.\n\nThe reporter's `psql` error likely has a different root cause (container not ready, stale volume, etc.). A comment explaining this was prepared but the token lacks write access.", "additional_kwargs": {"refusal": null}, "response_metadata": {"token_usage": {"completion_tokens": 388, "prompt_tokens": 7008, "total_tokens": 7396, "completion_tokens_details": {"accepted_prediction_tokens": null, "audio_tokens": 0, "reasoning_tokens": 18, "rejected_prediction_tokens": null, "image_tokens": 0}, "prompt_tokens_details": {"audio_tokens